{"key":"processedPost-8608785","value":{"id":8608785,"first":8608591,"last":8610236,"when":1215554357,"utime":"07/09/08 12:59 AM","content":"I prefer to use the needle or scalpel as soon as it's 'cool' without wiping.&nbsp; Normally, a drop or two of solution can be squeezed out from a red hot needle and it's ready to use.&nbsp; If it's a scalpel, the fist swipe through the petri dish or mushroom flesh sizzles it enough to cool for a sterile transfer.&nbsp; <br /><br />After a scalpel or needle has been repeatly heated, they don't really turn red anymore.&nbsp; I've noticed this for years.&nbsp; That's usually when it's become dull anyway, so it's time to change.&nbsp; Brand new needles and scalpel blades will turn red hot very quickly.&nbsp; If you're using a very old blade or needle, simply hold it over the flame for 15 to 30 seconds and that should take care of any bacteria present.<br />RR","title":"Re: flaming scalpels and tweezers"}}